  "text": "It is widely accepted that a to-be-learned item benefits most from repetition when additional items are introduced before it is repeated than when learning presentations occur in immediate succession. This \"spacing effect\" is already shaping clinical and educational practices, but its underlying mechanisms and the extent of its effectiveness across a range of populations are not yet fully understood (for a review, see [CITATION_1] . For this technique to reach its potential in applied settings, it is important to delineate how and under what conditions it works best. Here, we investigate the potential of the spacing effect to provide rehabilitation benefits in a unique person with developmental amnesia. After validating a short-term list-learning paradigm in which retention interval was held constant across massed (immediate succession) and spaced conditions, we examined whether spacing benefits would persist in a long-term paired associate paradigm.",
